latestPosts.caption:
Nothing has officially launched its much-awaited Nothing Phone (3) in India, and just as the leaks suggested, the smartphone carries forward the brand’s signature transparent aesthetic with a fresh twist. This time, Nothing has modified the Glyph Interface, making it more functional and interactive than ever before.

Refined Transparent Design with Enhanced Glyph Interface

At first glance, the Nothing Phone (3) looks familiar, retaining the transparent back panel and minimalist design language that the brand is known for. However, the biggest highlight is the revamped Glyph Interface.

This interface uses micro-LED lighting on the rear panel to provide visual feedback for calls, notifications, charging progress, and more. The new version is more customizable and can potentially integrate with additional apps and features in future updates, offering users a truly unique smartphone experience.

Display and Performance

The Nothing Phone (3) sports a premium display with an in-display fingerprint sensor for quick and secure unlocking. Under the hood, it is powered by the Qualcomm Snapdragon 8s Gen 4 processor, delivering flagship-grade performance whether you’re gaming, multitasking, or using AI-powered apps.

Impressive Camera Setup

Photography enthusiasts will appreciate the versatile triple 50MP camera setup on the back, which includes:
 • A 50MP main camera for crisp shots in all lighting conditions
 • A 50MP periscope lens for enhanced zoom capabilities
 • A 50MP ultra-wide camera for expansive landscapes and group photos

On the front, there’s a 50MP selfie camera, ensuring your selfies look detailed and vibrant.

Battery and Software Updates

The device packs a substantial 5,500mAh battery, promising all-day power without compromise. Like its predecessors, the Nothing Phone (3) runs on a clean Android experience and offers 3 years of Android updates along with 4 years of security updates, keeping your phone secure and up to date.

Storage and Color Options

Nothing Phone (3) is available in White and Black color options and comes in a base variant of 12GB RAM with 256GB storage, providing ample space for apps, media, and files.

Final Thoughts

I was not ready for that Dyson one 💀

One of the best trips away with my best friends to Peru! 
1. Being up in the clouds at Machu Picchu felt ETHEREAL
2. Alpacas EVERYWHERE
3. We went through literally every type of climate 
4. But the views were continuously worth it
5. Cusco was the coolest city, the entire thing is over 3,000m above sea level in the mountains
6. Hopped over to the Amazon rainforest, looking for alligators and more
7. Failed on the alligator hunt, but did manage to catch a tiger fish as consolation 
8. Amazon rainforest treetop views were magical (and a near-death experience to get to)
9. Cruising on Amazon riverboats (almost everyone’s hats flew off their heads and will never be seen again 🥲)
10. Jungle exploring
11. Found a ginger plant, which is a natural shampoo people still use!
12. Trying local oranges and limes (WAY more sour than western ones), which form the basis of ceviche
13. Even more vistas
14. Squad photo 😎

Took a 10 day break in the Maldives and THIS PLACE IS LITERALLY HEAVEN ON EARTH. 🏖️ From left to right:

1. Surreal sunsets (cause there is nothing blocking the horizons)
2. You can always see the sea (even on the toilet)
3. You can see sharks literally 1 metre from the shoreline 
4. I like sharks
5. The islands are incredibly lush
6. Best tasting seafood I’ve ever had
7. Best tasting pasta Dhrisha has ever had (she’s veggie lol)
8. I was trying to do something weird so I’d remember the hol more vividly 
9. We fully switched off all our tech for 4 days (SO hard at the start, SO rewarding by the end) 
10. Hotel decor was wild
11. We take our board games everywhere 
12. Did I mention the Maldives are lush? 🥹
13. Anti-gravity yoga (my back still hurts from it)
14. I looked bad so I just took photos of her
15. Overwater villas are SUCH A VIBE
16. Again I really like sharks
17. First time we’ve properly done scuba!
18. And what a place to do it 🥰
19. The tan is really kicking in
20. Uninterrupted view of the stars ✨

In our test, the iPhone took over 4 minutes to power on and eventually displayed a temperature warning alert once it finally booted up. In contrast, the Google Pixel powered on quickly without any issues. Based on this real-world performance, the Pixel clearly outperformed the iPhone in this round.

However, looking deeper — between the two devices:

The phone that displays a warning after hot water exposure is actually doing the right thing. It’s alerting you to potential risks like overheating or moisture — a crucial safety feature designed to protect internal components.

On the other hand, a phone that powers on normally without any alerts might lack proper safety sensors. While it may seem fine, internal damage could go undetected — which can be risky in the long run.

So, while the Pixel wins this round on speed, the iPhone’s warning system shows it’s prioritizing long-term reliability and device protection. Sometimes, a delay with a warning is actually a sign of smarter engineering.
